(1)
Thirty-seventh Ave. (right), south side, west of Prince Street (formerly Garden Street), showing Hamilton Hall at the S.W. corner. This building was erected in 1803 at the corner of Main and Locust Streets at a cost of $1250. It then belonged to St. George Episcopal Church. The building was converted into a sunday school in 1811. It was removed in 1860 to the present site. In 1926 its number was 133-48-50 Thirty-seventh Ave.

1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(2)
The same, another view. Eugene L. Armbruster has it that this building was originally St. George's Academy and stood on church property. In 1805 it became Hamilton Hall, an independent academy, then it again reverted to the church.

1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

37th Ave., at and adjoining the N.W. corner of Prince St. In the foreground is a view of the Reformed Church of Flushing. The congregation was organized in June 1842; the corner stone laid on August 16, 1843; and the edifice dedicated on September 10, 1844. The Rev. A. Gordon was its first pastor. The building was demolished in 1925. Note: this building was not designated as a church in the Realty Atlas of Queens for 1891. The cost of the edifice was twelve thousand dollars. It was enlarged in 1859. In 1925 a garage occupied the site of this church. A new structure was erected in 1892 at the corner of Amity and Bowne Sts.

Views: 1-3 1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

Thirty-seventh Ave., south side, east of Prince Street. The first fully seen house was occupied by John Hefferman for fifty years.

1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

Thirty-seventh Ave., (left) at the N.W. corner of Prince Street (foreground), showing (what the writer believes to be) the Reformed Church of Flushing which was built of granite quarried at Blackwells (now, Welfare) Island. The congregation organized in June 1842 and the cornerstone being laid on August 16, 1843. In 1891 it does not appear as a church in the Realty Atlas of Queens and in 1925 was demolished. This set consists of a negative and a positive.

About 1925.

A. A. Russell.
Gift of Albert A. Volk Co.

Prince Street, at the N.E. corner of 37th Avenue. The corner house was owned, in 1873, by T. Fogarty, and the one adjoining it (left) by Mrs. Burling.

P. L. Sperr
June 28, 1940

Prince Street, at the S.E. corner of 37th Avenue, viewing toward the latter and showing old homes. The corner house was owned, in 1873, by one having the initials P.F.(probably P. Fogarty), according to Beers's 1873 map.

P. L. Sperr

June 28, 1940
